---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="DST Tool" description="DST — Deterministic Security Testing engine">
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>DST Engine</h1>

    <h2>Quick Start</h2>

    <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/MassDeterministicEngines/dst-engine.git
cd dst-engine
npm install --legacy-peer-deps
npx tsx src/dst-cli.ts --demo --prove</code></pre>

    <h2>What You'll See</h2>

    <p>
      DST parses source code into a graph, traces tainted data flows, verifies 783 CWE
      properties, and generates proof certificates for exploitable findings:
    </p>

    <pre><code>[FAIL] CWE-89: SQL Injection
  CRITICAL: User input from req.body.login flows to SQL query
  at db.query(query, ...) without parameterization.
    Source: req.body.login (line 10)
    Sink:   db.query(query, ...) (line 11)
    Missing: CONTROL (input validation or parameterized query)
    PROOF [strong]:
      Payload: ' UNION SELECT 'DST_CANARY_SQLI' --
      Deliver: http POST /
      Oracle:  hybrid — payload reaches sink unmodified</code></pre>

    <p>
      That <code>PROOF</code> block is the difference. DST doesn't just say
      "this looks vulnerable" &mdash; it gives you the payload to prove it.
    </p>

    <h2>Architecture</h2>

    <pre><code>Source code → tree-sitter AST
  → Phoneme classification (API calls → universal semantic types)
  → NeuralMap graph (nodes + tainted data flow edges)
  → CWE verification (783 properties checked against graph)
  → Proof generation (payload + delivery + oracle per finding)</code></pre>

    <h2>Supported Languages</h2>

    <p>
      <strong>Benchmarked:</strong> Java, JavaScript/TypeScript<br />
      <strong>Profiles built:</strong> Python, Go, Rust, PHP, C#, Ruby, Kotlin, Swift
    </p>

    <h2>AI Security Extensions</h2>

    <p>
      DST's phoneme architecture extends naturally to AI/LLM security. With ~190 lines
      of mapper code (LLM SDK phonemes + a taint-transformer rule), DST can detect
      67.9% of the AI security vulnerability landscape &mdash; including Text2SQL injection,
      prompt injection (CWE-1427), and MCP server vulnerabilities.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href="/research">Read the research &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
